Linear Model 01: OLS Regression¶

We use scikit-learn's LinearRegression and LinearRegressionCV objects to fit an unregularized linear model and a linear model with the lasso penalty parameter chosen through cross-validation.

In [7]:
# The only preprocessing we'll perform is one hot encoding or dummificaton of categorical features
gitters_lin_reg_preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ('cat_transformer', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs)
    ]
)

# We combine this column transformation step with a Linear Regression predictr 
gitters_lin_reg_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps = [
        ('preprocessor', gitters_lin_reg_preprocessor), 
        ('regressor', LinearRegression())
    ]
)

# Train the model
gitters_lin_reg_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Use it to make predictions and compute MAE 
gitters_lin_reg_pred = gitters_lin_reg_pipeline.predict(X_test)
gitters_lin_reg_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true = y_test, y_pred = gitters_lin_reg_pred)

print(f"MAE for OLS Linear Regression: {np.round(gitters_lin_reg_mae, 2)}")

MAE for OLS Linear Regression: 353.07

Linear Model 02: Lasso Regression¶

For the lasso regression, we also want to standardize the numeric columns in addition to dummifying the categorical columns. This is best done with a Pipeline object in conjunction with a ColumnTransformer that combines a OneHotEncoder and a StandardScaler.

In [8]:
# Instantiate a preprocessing transformer
gitters_lasso_reg_preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ('cat_transformer', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs), 
        ('num_transformer', StandardScaler(), num_attribs)
    ]
)

# Combine with a regressor in the pipeline with a LassoCV regressor
# LassoCV regressor receives a pre-initialized list of alpha values (regularization strength)
alpha_grid = 10.0 ** np.arange(-5, 5, 1)
gitters_lasso_reg_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps = [
        ('preprocessor', gitters_lasso_reg_preprocessor), 
        ('cv_lasso_regressor', LassoCV(alphas = alpha_grid, verbose = 1))
    ]
)

# Fit to training data
gitters_lasso_reg_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

Feedforward Neural Network¶

We first preprocess the features to make sure we have input tensors for the right dimensions and scale for both training and test data.

This is also important because we need to know the dimensions of the input data before we can instantiate the ANN.

In [10]:
# Create a preprocessor for the neural network's features
gitters_ann_preprocessor = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', ColumnTransformer([
        ('one_hot_encoder', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs), 
        ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler(), num_attribs)
    ]))
])

# Use the training data to learn the mean/SD for standardization of numeric features
# and the categories for encoding the categorical features 
gitters_ann_X_train = gitters_ann_preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train, y_train)

# Having learnt these parameters, use them to modify the test set predictors 
gitters_ann_X_test = gitters_ann_preprocessor.transform(X_test)

We then compile the ANN model by specifying the following hyperparameters

  • loss: which function to use to compute loss which, in turn, can be used as a signal for optimising weights
  • optimizer: which variant of gradient descent to use for optimising the weights
  • metrics: quantities to track during training/validation
In [14]:
# Before we train the model, we need to compile it to specify hyperparameters
gitters_ann.compile(
    loss = 'mse', optimizer = 'RMSprop', metrics = ['mean_absolute_error']
)

We now fit the model while specifying some more hyperparameters

  • batch_size: how many randomly sampled data points from the training set will be used for each step of gradient descent step.
  • epochs: how many full passes through the training data need to be made during training
  • validation_data: optional data to use for checking outsample performance with every epoch

I have removed the output from the gitters_ann.fit command to make the Notebook more readable.

    verbose = 1

Both the MSE and MAE show the same trend: surprisingly, error is higher in the training data and less on the test data. This might be because the data points in the test set are "easier" than the ones in the training set. However, we expect to see the opposite in real world examples: training MSE/MAE will be lower than validation test.

We now use the neural network to predict on the test set and check its MA using the weights from the end of training.

The feedforward neural network has the lowest test set MAE on this data set, followed by lasso regression and OLS linear regression.

This is a bit counterintuitive because the lasso regressor is the most regularized, while the feedforward neural network has the highest propensity to overfit.

Example 02 - Multilayer Network on MNIST Data¶

Preprocessing¶

In [ ]:
The `keras` package comes with a number of example data sets, including the `MNIST` handwritten digits data set. We load this data and preprocess it i.e.
- extract training and test set features and predictors 
- check shapes of all tensors 
- one-hot encode the target
- rescale the features to have mean 0.
In [75]:
# Load the data
(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test) = mnist.load_data()

# Check shapes of each tensor 
print("X_train:\t", X_train.shape)
print("X_test:\t\t", X_test.shape)
print("y_train:\t", y_train.shape)
print("y_test:\t\t", y_test.shape)

X_train:	 (60000, 28, 28)
X_test:		 (10000, 28, 28)
y_train:	 (60000,)
y_test:		 (10000,)

We have 60,000 examples in the training set and 10,000 examples in the test set. Each example is a $28 \times 28$ array of pixel intensities in the range $[0, 255]$. We want to reshape the training arrays to $28 \times 28 = 784$-dimensional vectors.

The targets y_test and y_train contains numbers from 1 - 9 indicating class of the digit. We can one-hot encode this with a built-in keras function called to_categorical.

In [76]:
X_train = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1] * X_train.shape[2])
X_test = X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1] * X_test.shape[2])

# After reshaping 
print("X_train:\t", X_train.shape)
print("X_test:\t\t", X_test.shape)

# Now scale to get min value of 0 and max value of 1
X_train =  X_train / 255.0
X_test = X_test / 255.0

print(f"Min X_train: {np.min(X_train)} | Max X_train: {np.max(X_train)}")
print(f"Min X_test: {np.min(X_test)} | Max X_train: {np.max(X_test)}")

# One-hot encode the targets 
print(f"Before one-hot: y_train_shape: {y_train.shape} | y_test_shape: {y_test.shape}")
y_train = to_categorical(y_train)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test)

# Shape of the target arrays will have changed 
print(f"After one-hot: y_train_shape: {y_train.shape} | y_test_shape: {y_test.shape}")

Training Network¶

Now that data has been preprocessed, we can instantiate a multi-layer feedforward neural network.

In [80]:
mnist_ann = keras.models.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Input(shape = (X_train.shape[1], )),

We have use padding = 'same' argument for each Conv2D layer to ensure the output channels have the same dimensins as the input channels.

There are 32 channels in the first hidden layer in contrast to the 3 channels in the original image. The number of channels continues to increase with every Conv2D layer.

We have used $2 \times 2$ blocks for pooling and $3 \times 3$ convolutional filter in each layer.

We finally Flatten a high-dimensional output from our final Conv2D-MaxPooling2D layer into a single tensor of high-level features, followed by Dropout regularization.

The final layers is a Dense softmax over all the classes.

Decoding Reviews¶

In [384]:
X_train[1][1:10] # Look at first 10 words numeric codes
Out[384]:
[194, 1153, 194, 8255, 78, 228, 5, 6, 1463]

To see the actual words that these integer indexes represent, we write a function decode_review.

In [385]:
# IMDb data has its own internal word-index mapping. Read it as dictionary
word_index = imdb.get_word_index()

# We modify this mapping by reversing key/value pairs, and adding 4 tokens
my_word_keys = list(word_index.keys())
my_word_idx = list(word_index.values()) 

my_word_keys = ['<PAD>', '<START>', '<UNK>', '<UNUSED>'] + my_word_keys
my_word_idx = [0, 1, 2, 3] + list(np.array(my_word_idx) + 3)

# In our custom word mapping, we perform a lookup on the word index 
# and return the corresponding word. If word index is missing, we return <UNK>
custom_word_index = dict(zip(my_word_idx, my_word_keys))

def decode_review(text, word_idx_dict = custom_word_index):
    decoded_text = ' '.join([word_idx_dict.get(word_int, 2) for word_int in text])
    return decoded_text
In [386]:
# Initialize a test review that can be used to check `decode_review`
test_review = [
    1, 14, 22, 16, 43, 530, 973, 1622, 1385, 65, 458, 4468
]
decode_review(test_review)
Out[386]:
"<START> this film was just brilliant casting location scenery story direction everyone's"

The matches the decoded string that was printed in the book, so our implementation of this function is correct.

One-Hot Encoding for Bag of Words¶

We want to write a function that will convert a sequence of integers representing a review into a one-hot encoded tensor of dimension 10,000 (the same as our vocabulary size). When a word appears in the review, its corresponding index in the dictionary is looked up and set to 1. The remainder of the words are 0.

Ideally, this should be a sparse matrix.

In [387]:
# Dictionary size 
n_words = 10000

# Initialize empty arrays with one row per sample and one column per word 
# Separately for training and test data
X_train_1h = np.zeros(shape = (X_train.shape[0], n_words))
X_test_1h = np.zeros(shape = (X_test.shape[0], n_words))
In [388]:
# Iterate over each row in training set, find the corresponding unique words, 
# set their indexes in X_train_1h to 1.0 
for i in range(X_train.shape[0]):
    X_train_1h[i, np.unique(X_train[i])] = 1.0
In [389]:
# Do the same on the test data
for i in range(X_test.shape[0]):
    X_test_1h[i, np.unique(X_test[i])] = 1.0

We see clear evidence of overfitting here. Just aftet two epochs, the validation loss reaches its minimum and begins to increase. We see a similar trend in validation accuracy, where the initial optimisation makes the accuacy close to 88% but there is not much improvement with increasing epochs.

By 20 epochs, the training loss is almost 0 and training accuracy is almost 1, suggesting severe overfitting.

Ideally, an early stopping callback should have been used with this model to rollback weights to those of epoch 2. The weights from epoch 20 will likely not generalize well to new data.

In [423]:

print(f"ANN Accuracy: {np.round(imdb_ann_accuracy, 2)}")

ANN Accuracy: 0.85

This is sort of expected. We can see from the training history that, at its best, the outsample accuracy was slightly higher than that of the lasso regressor i.e. 89% compared to 88%. However, because of overfitting to the training data, the final weights don't generalize well to test data, resulting in a neural network that underperforms compared to a logisitic regression.

We should bear in mind that logistic regression model was heavily regularized (selecting only 25% of all predictors) whereas no such regularization took place in the NN.

Embedding LSTM¶

Instead of one-hot encoding the words like we did last time, we will simply feed the 500-dimensional integer representation of each document to en Embedding layer, which condenses this to a lower-dimensional representation while preserving the semantic structure of the document. The layer one-hot encodes the data on its own - we don't need to do it this time.

Important distinction make here

  • the input to the networks is a 500-dimensional tensor
  • however, the values of this 500-dimensional tensor are actually from a 10,000-dimensional space representing our dictionary
  • goal is to condense these 10,000 words into a 32-dimensional space while preserving contextual and semantic information.

The LSTM layer is used for the idea of recurrence: weight optimisations for a given word will depend on the activations generated by previous words as well. This will help encode a sense of sequence and context in the network.

In [455]:
imdb_embed_lstm_ann = keras.models.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Input(shape = (X_train.shape[1], )), 
    keras.layers.Embedding(input_dim = 10000, output_dim = 32), 
    keras.layers.LSTM(units = 32),
    keras.layers.Dense(units = 1, activation = 'sigmoid')
])

print(imdb_embed_lstm_ann.summary())

Because in a production environment, we wouldn't have visbility of DJ_return and log_volatility until we had visibility of log_volume.

Recurrent Neural Network - Without day_of_week¶

The RNN expects input to be a sequence or $L = 5$ feature vectors $X = \{X_l\}^L_1$ for each observation in the data frame.

These feature vectors represent lagged versions of the time series going back $L$ time steps.

features_train_rnn = features_train.values.reshape(n_train, 5, 3)
features_test_rnn = features_test.values.reshape(n_test, 5, 3)

Feed Forward Neural Network - With day_of_week¶

To replicate the logic of a non-linear autoregression model, we don't use a recurrent neural network. Instead, we just use a feedforward neural network with the day-wise lagged features and one-hot encoded day_of_week features as predictors.
